names:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mandeville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Armand, Gabrielle, Camille, Emile, Fernand, Fernande, Gaston, Jean-Paul, Lucien, Michel.","French: habitational name from Mandeville, the name of two places in Normandy, derived from Latin <i>magna villa</i> ‘large estate’, or a variant of <b>Manneville</b>, a habitational name from Manneville, the name of several places in Normandy (see 2 below). Compare   Montville   and   Monville  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Manneville (Seine-Maritime, Calvados), Manneville-sur-Risle (Eure), or Magneville (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Mansfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place so named in Nottinghamshire. The placename means ‘open land by the river Maun’, from the river name Maun (which may take its name from a hill named with Old English <i>mamme</i> ‘teat’) + Old English <i>feld</i> ‘open country’.","Irish (Waterford): when not an importation of 1, this is an altered form of the Norman name <b>de Manville</b> (see   Mandeville   3).","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) <b>Mansfeld</b>, a habitational name from a place so called in Saxony."]},{"name":"Manderville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Manwell","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Manville","meanings":["English (Sussex and Lancashire): variant of   Mandeville  .","Altered form of   Mainville   1, a surname of Swiss French origin (see   Miville  ).","French: variant of <b>Menville</b>, a habitational name from Menville in Haute-Garonne, and also of   Mainville   2."]},{"name":"Mundell","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  .","Americanized form of German <b>Mündel</b> (or some other similar, like-sounding surname): nickname for someone with a prominent mouth, from Middle High German <i>munt</i>, <i>mündelīn</i> ‘(little) mouth’."]},{"name":"Monville","meanings":["Altered form of French   Mandeville  .","Walloon: habitational name from Monville in Namur province in Wallonia (Belgium), of the same etymology as in 3 below.","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from Montville in Seine-Maritime or Monville in Calvados, both named with Old French <i>mont</i> ‘mountain, hill’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’."]},{"name":"Mandal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Chandi, Sanjay, Sankar, Somnath, Aditi, Aditya, Ajit, Amala, Amitabha, Anil, Anirudh, Aparna.","Indian (northern states): from Sanskrit <i>maṇḍala</i>, a word that has several meanings, including ‘sphere’ and ‘halo’.","English (Cumbria; of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Montville","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Vernice.","Altered form of French   Mandeville  .","French: variant of   Monville  . This surname is very rare in France, found mainly in Creuse."]},{"name":"Manfull","meanings":["English (Midlands): probably a variant of   Mandeville  . Compare   Manville  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":49,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Walter De Mandeville was born about 1210, in Staffordshire, England. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Alice Giffard. He died in 1267, in Cornwall, England, at the age of 58."},"et":{"about 1210–1267":"umbes 1210–1267","1240–1308":"1240–1308","1264–1307":"1264–1307","–1288":"–1288","1210–1267":"1210–1267","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1267":"1267","1288":"1288","29 September 1264":"29. september 1264","1210":"1210","1264":"1264","1240":"1240","about 1210":"umbes 1210","1308":"1308","1307":"1307","Cornwall, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Luton, Bedfordshire, 